  "prompt": "What is the difference between AT&T DSL and U-verse DSL?",
  "response": "AT&T offers two types of internet services: AT&T DSL and AT&T U-verse. While both services use a phone line to deliver internet, there are some key differences between the two:\n\n1. Technology: AT&T DSL uses a traditional copper phone line to deliver internet service. On the other hand, AT&T U-verse uses fiber-optic technology to deliver internet, TV, and phone services. This means that U-verse can offer faster speeds and more reliable service than traditional DSL.\n\n2. Speed: U-verse offers faster internet speeds than traditional DSL. While AT&T DSL typically offers speeds up to 6 Mbps, U-verse can offer speeds up to 100 Mbps or more, depending on the plan you choose.\n\n3. Availability: AT&T DSL is widely available throughout the country, while U-verse is only available in select areas where AT&T has invested in its fiber-optic network.\n\n4. Bundling: U-verse allows you to bundle your internet, TV, and phone services into one package, while AT&T DSL is typically only offered as a standalone internet service.\n\nIn summary, while both AT&T DSL and U-verse use a phone line to deliver internet, U-verse uses fiber-optic technology to offer faster speeds and more reliable service. However, U-verse is only available in select areas, while AT&T DSL is more widely available.",
